XML_CASESUMMARY.SUMMARY:
This is a two-vehicle crash that occurred in the intersection of two, two way, 5-lane roadways. The east/west roadway has three eastbound lanes and two westbound lanes separated by double yellow lines. The north/south roadway has three southbound lanes and two northbound lanes separated by double yellow lines. Operating overhead traffic signals with pedestrian lights controls traffic at the intersection. Both roadways were straight and level with a bituminous surface. The posted speed limit is 56 kmph (35 mph) for southbound traffic and 40 kmph (25 mph) for southbound traffic. The time of the crash was mid morning on a weekday. The road was dry and the sky was clear. There were no sight restrictions.
Vehicle one (V1) a 1995 Dodge Intrepid 4 door with one occupant, was traveling east in the number two lane approaching the intersection. Vehicle two (V2), a 2004 Ford Taurus 4 door with one occupant, was traveling south in the number two lane. As both vehicles entered the intersection, the front of V2 struck the left side of V1. Both vehicles rotated and the vehicles side slapped as the right side of V2 struck the left side of V1. Both vehicles came to rest facing southeast in the intersection. Both vehicles were towed due to damage. Both drivers were examined on scene by EMS personnel but were not transported.
V1 was driven by a 62-year-old male who was in good general health, was not taking any medications, did wear glasses and slept a total of 9 hours the night before in his residence. He stated that he was going east in the number two lane, thought he had a green light and drove through the intersection. He also stated that he was daydreaming. He stated that he did not know where he was coming from or where he was going. He thought he was traveling about 20 mph. The driver is familiar with the vehicle and drives the route daily. A witness traveling behind V2 stated that V2 had the green light as it traveled thru the intersection. The Critical Reason for the Critical Event was "driver related factor-inattention (daydreaming)". The Critical Pre Crash Event was "this vehicle traveling, crossing over (passing through) an intersection.
The driver of V2 was a 71-year-old male who was in good health, was wearing prescription glasses and taking prescription medications Zocor and Ativan. He stated that he slept 8.5 hours the night before at his residence. He had been driving about 5 minutes before the crash and was going to an attorney's office. He stated he was traveling south in the number two lane approaching the intersection on a green light. The light was till green after he entered the intersection. He is familiar with the vehicle and drives the route daily. The Critical Reason for the Critical event was not coded to this vehicle. The Critical Pre Crash Event was coded "other vehicle encroachment, from crossing street, across the path".
